<TEXT>
dr harold glendon scheie founder and 
former director of the scheie eye institute of philadelphia died 
in his sleep on monday he was 80 years old 
scheie died of cancer said sarah jarvis a spokeswoman for the 
hospital of the university of pennsylvania 
scheie was dedicated to the advancement of ophthalmic science 
and patient care for more than 55 years and his research findings 
had a profound effect on eye care throughout the world 
scheie was responsible for the development of key surgical 
techniques including the treatment of congenital cataracts and 
glaucoma he also helped develop the diagnostic test for myasthenia 
gravis with dr george gammon in the late 1930s 
scheie was the first to describe in detail the rare inherited 
metabolic disease that can cloud the cornea now called scheies 
syndrome 
many of todays ophthalmogical instruments and procedures bear 
his name including the scheie procedure used in glaucoma surgery 
dr william n kelly executive vice president of the university 
of pennsylvania and dean of the school of medicine described 
scheie as a pioneer in ophthalmic sciences 
from the beginning of his professional career as the 
hospitals first resident in ophthalmology it was clear that great 
things would come from harold g scheie kelly said the scheie 
eye institute is but one example of his many accomplishments 
the institute opened in 1972 with scheie as its director the 
total eyecare facility houses the department of ophthalmology of 
penns school of medicine and is based at presbyterian medical 
center of philadelphia 
scheie was a native of brookings sd he graduated with honors 
in 1935 from the university of minnesota school of medicine and 
later moved to philadelphia 
scheies interest in ophthalmic science developed during his 
twoyear internship at the hospital of the university of 
pennsylvania in 1935 
he is survived by his wife mary ann tallman son eric scheie 
of berkeley calif and daughter nancy scheie of somerville nj 
services for scheie were scheduled at the arlington national 
cemetery chapel in arlington va for march 13 a memorial service 
will be held at the university of pennsylvania on march 19 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

