<TEXT>
amidullahs shoerepair shop is a 
rough wooden box in which he can barely stand erect he is 9 years 
old and has been the chief support of a large family since his 
father was killed two months ago 
in the muddy market lanes of kabul small boys and old men 
compete for jobs pulling carts loaded with sacks of soviet flour 
japanese television sets and cartons of west german hand lotion 
the human mules even tow shiny red motorbikes to showrooms rather 
than ride them 
most young men seen in the capital are in uniform the others 
usually are on crutches their feet or entire legs lost to land 
mines in a dozen years of civil war 
in a factory outside a military base about 1000 women make 
army uniforms only 20 percent are married but about 50 percent 
have become pregnant one said shaking her head sadly she and 
others said prostitution is a disturbing new phenomenon in kabul 
life has never been easy in this ancient land whose name 
conjures mystery intrigue and adventure today the traditional 
hardscrabble existence is compounded by a war that has produced 
neither victor nor vanquished and wont go away 
afghanistans descent into war began in 1973 when mohammad daoud 
deposed his cousin king zahir shah while the king was abroad 
daoud was assassinated in april 1978 in a communist coup 
the kremlin sent military forces in december 1979 to rescue its 
proteges from internal power struggles and a war with moslem 
guerrillas the insurgents get most of their support from the 
united states pakistan and saudi arabia 
in the 12 years since the 1978 coup the party has changed 
leaders twice by assassination and once in a power play either 
engineered or supported by the soviets that installed president 
najib in 1986 
soviet combat forces withdrew a year ago leaving the afghan 
army to fight the guerrillas alone 
to the surprise of the united states and others government 
troops have not merely held their own but have expanded their area 
of control reopening supply routes and making deals with local 
guerrilla commanders 
limited success has come at a high price 
the government says half its resources go the war effort in a 
chaotic economy children and teenagers who work as manual 
laborers and prostitutes earn more than their fathers who have 
government jobs according to interviews with kabul residents of 
all social levels 
i think this war is making us more backward said a kabul 
professional educated in eastern europe who insisted his name not 
be used 
the generation of 12 to 15yearolds they will be 
illiterate you will have a generation sick with noneducation 
with heroin and hashish this is a result of i dont know war 
revolution government peoples hate its very sad 
in his wooden cubicle which he opened soon after his father 
died in an auto crash barefoot amidullah handed a pair of highly 
polished black boots to a customer 
he said he earned about 100 afghanis a day three times what his 
12yearold brother wahidullah makes working in a bakery amidullah 
is the main breadwinner for his mother and his seven brothers and 
sisters 
at the unrealistic official rate amidullahs earnings translate 
to 181 a day but amount to only 20 cents at the more accurate 
black market rate 
amidullah said the combined earnings of the two brothers were 
sometimes enough for food sometimes not 
said omar sells rocklike lumps of brown crudely refined sugar 
at the mujahedeen market on kabuls outskirts the market got its 
name because the goods sold there are from territory held by the 
guerrillas who call themselves mujahedeen or holy warriors 
omar 48 said he had four sons and three daughters and 
number eight child is coming he and 10yearold zalmai sat on 
their cart of sugar shielded from the cold rain by a tarpaulin of 
bright orange 
some days i am not eating lunch because if i eat lunch my 
family wont have food omar said 
no one in his family has been killed or wounded in the war but 
rockets fell near his house not long ago 
i am afraid of the rockets he said i made a sort of hole 
under my house when the rockets come i go with my family 
underground 
kabul has its pockets of affluence of fancy houses big cars 
lavish weddings glitzy sweaters and acidwashed jeans 
mohammad jamil who is 42 and has four children reckons he has 
a good job because he sells cars on commission rather than working 
for a salary but times are still bad 
five years ago we were selling and buying five or six cars a 
day he said just now we cant sell one car in a month 
in january he sold a 1983 mercedes benz to a rich merchant for 
7 million afghanis 14000 on the black market jamils 1 percent 
commission brought him 70000 afghanis 140 or 20000 more than 
president najibs official monthly salary 
</TEXT>
