<TEXT>
north carolinas 84 death row inmates wont 
go free but many of their lives could be spared under a us 
supreme court ruling overturning a key part of the states 
deathpenalty law authorities said 
the court monday set aside the death sentence of dock mckoy jr 
for the 1984 murder of a deputy sheriff because under the state 
law the sentencing jury couldnt consider any mitigating factor 
or one that might lessen the sentence unless all 12 jurors agreed 
writing for the court justice thurgood marshall said the 
unanimity requirement is unconstitutional chief justice william h 
rehnquist and justices antonin scalia and sandra day oconnor 
dissented in the 63 vote 
the opinion itself is just very sweeping said gordon 
widenhouse assistant appellate defender for the state were 
ecstatic 
the decision does not mean that any death row inmates will go 
free but it does mean that as many as 70 convicted murderers must 
have new sentencing hearings attorney general lacy thornburg 
said it means in each case that another jury will be required to 
again decide the appropriate punishment 
eightytwo men are on death row at central prison in raleigh and 
two women have been sentenced to die at the nc correctional 
institution for women also in raleigh said bill poston a state 
department of correction spokesman 
poston said officers at central prison gave word of the ruling 
to several of the inmates and asked them to spread the news poston 
said none of the inmates had expressed a reaction monday 
the state attorney generals office believes the ruling should 
affect only defendants who received death sentences beginning in 
1985 said jim coman senior deputy attorney general but im 
sure all the attorneys for all the death row inmates will appeal 
he said 
thornburg said he would ask the legislature to reexamine the 
death penalty law and make changes that will make the sentence of 
death more enforceable 
malcolm hunter jr the state appellate defender who challenged 
the north carolina law said he had not yet spoken with mckoy but 
he said he was not sure mckoy is really able to appreciate it 
hes over 70 in very poor mental emotional and physical 
health hes sort of a pathetic creature right now 
mckoy was convicted of shooting anson county deputy sheriff 
william kress horne three days before christmas 1984 
neighbors reported that mckoy was drinking and shooting and the 
sheriffs department responded once and asked him to stop when 
deputies were called to the house a second time deputies asked 
mckoy to step outside 
instead he opened a screen door and fired his gun shooting 
horne who was standing behind his patrol car with his pistol drawn 
at his trial mckoy had offered an insanity defense 
