<TEXT>
a state lawmaker on tuesday withstood a 
recall election brought by opponents of indian spearfishing 
handily defeating his challenger 
democratic rep james holperin the first state lawmaker to face 
a recall since 1932 had 9535 votes or 69 percent to 4380 or 31 
percent for sayner businessman gene ahlborn with all precincts 
reporting unofficial returns showed 
holperin takes on republican brian sherren a st germain resort 
and recreational vehicle park owner on april 3 sherren although 
running unopposed in the gop primary garnered 601 votes 
earlier holperin said the voter turnout would be critical the 
recall election was brought by opponents of spearfishing rights for 
wisconsins chippewa indians 
i am very pleased with the outcome it is not a foregone 
conclusion that this is a guarantee of victory in april holperin 
told reporters at his campaign headquarters 
holperin said he was reluctant to read too much into the special 
election victory saying it only showed voters want him on the 
ballot next month and believed in the normal cycle of elections 
rather than recalls 
the recall was sparked by critics of indian spearfishing a 
right federal courts have said the states six chippewa bands 
retained in 19thcentury treaties with the us government 
the issue has caused years of unrest uncertainty and tension in 
northern wisconsin between indians who want to exercise a legal 
right and nonindians who complain their livelihoods are being 
destroyed 
organizers of the recall said holperin a fourterm incumbent 
had lost touch with his constituents on the issue and had failed to 
help reach an agreement to end the dispute 
the city clerk in rhinelander the largest town in holperins 
district which encompasses vilas and oneida counties said about 
21 percent of the eligible voters had cast ballots by midafternoon 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the recall has its roots in a 1983 federal court ruling that 
said wisconsins six chippewa bands retained the right to 
spearfish hunt cut timber and gather food on offreservation 
public lands under 19thcentury treaties that ceded northern 
wisconsin to the us government the ruling is under appeal 
vilas and oneida counties have been the scene of angry 
confrontations between nonindians and chippewa spearfishermen 
during tribal fishing seasons of recent years 
organizers of the recall were especially critical of holperins 
support last year for republican gov tommy g thompsons plan to 
lease the treaty rights of the lac du flambeau chippewa band for 10 
years 
the lac du flambeau would have received 50 million worth of 
cash and other aid in exchange for curtailing the exercise of 
treaty rights tribal members rejected the plan in a vote last fall 
holperin 39 a former radio and television newscaster was 
elected to the assembly in 1982 
