<TEXT>
the largely rural chinese province of shandong 
has enacted new regulations requiring all job applicants to undergo 
tests for venereal disease an official newspaper reported today 
the regulations were drawn up after the coastal province 
recorded 2690 cases of vd in 1989 a more than fourfold increase 
over the previous year the china daily said 
authorities may now require all applicants for jobs in state or 
collectivelyrun enterprises to prove they are free of venereal 
diseases and can ask health centers to carry out vd tests on 
prostitutes criminals and vagrants 
couples will be allowed to marry only after proving they are 
vdfree the report said doctors may not give private treatment to 
vd patients without the authorization of local health offices 
the daily said the rise of extramarital sex was the main reason 
for the rapid spread of vd in the province 
china in 1964 announced it had eliminated vd from the country 
but has acknowledged that sexual diseases have made a strong 
comeback in the 1980s as a result of increased contact with the 
outside world a revival of prostitution and changing attitudes 
toward sex 
the nation has recorded more than 200000 cases of vd since the 
early 1980s with the southern provinces bordering hong kong 
chinas most open areas among the hardest hit 
but the spread of vd is also being taken seriously in more 
remote areas such as shandong which has relatively few direct 
contacts with the outside world 
the national government now requires all foreigners taking up 
residency in china to show proof they are free from vd and aids 
chinese returning from three months or more abroad must also show 
documents they are not infected by the diseases 
</TEXT>
