highest priority and that all investigativetype resources should 
be directed toward bringing to justice those individuals who are 
guilty ms tutwiler added 
the fbi has sent forensic experts to guatemala to help in the 
investigations 
while the united states has provided substantial assistance to 
increase the investigative capacity of the police and the judicial 
system the perpetrators have still not been subjected to the 
rule of law ms tutwiler said 
given this situation the secretary of state has requested 
that ambassador stroock return to the united states to review the 
situation 
guatemalan government spokeswoman claudia arenas bianchi said in 
a telephone interview in guatemala city there is no temporary 
withdrawal of ambassador stroock he only left for meetings at the 
department of state 
cerezo and his christian democrats blame a rightist campaign to 
destabilize the government including two coup attempts last year 
by army officers but foreign diplomats and government critics 
blame cerezo for incompetence and say he is paralyzed by fear of 
rightwing violence 
the united states wants an investigation into last summers 
killings of five university students and several leftwing 
activists including one american 
many of the 77 politically motivated killings listed by human 
rights groups since last summer have been attributed to rightwing 
activists some foreign diplomats say the methods in some of the 
killings point to involvement by state security forces 
but ms tutwiler said the united states does not know who is 
responsible 
guatemalas democracy continues to be challenged by acts of 
terrorism and human rights abuses perpetrated by extremists who 
seek to undermine the democratically elected civilian government 
the spokeswoman said 
the united states government condemns these acts in the 
strongest terms and reiterates its fundamental support for the 
government of guatemala and for the peaceful transition through 
open and free elections to a new civilian government next year 
she said 
the violence in guatemala has dimmed hopes that a working 
democracy can take root in the central american country 
guatemala returned to civilian government in 1986 after three 
decades of military rule in which an estimated 100000 people died 
and 40000 disappeared the countrys previous experience with 
democracy ended in 1954 with a ciabacked coup against reformist 
president jacobo arbenz 
the guatemalan people deserve nothing less than what so many 
other nations of the hemisphere have achieved an open democratic 
system in which the rule of law is enforced and the rights and 
liberties of all guatemalans are protected ms tutwiler said 
</TEXT>
