<TEXT>
hog producers are enjoying some relatively 
good times and further improvement may be on the way says an 
agriculture department analysis 
returns have been on the upswing since last summer and could 
rise further during the second quarter as hog prices approach their 
seasonal peak the departments economic research service said 
market prices of slaughter hogs may reach the middle to upper 
50s per hundredweight before the end of june the highest in 
nearly three years the agency said in the march issue of 
agricultural outlook magazine so far prices in the first 
quarter have mostly been in the high 40s 
on monday top barrows and gilts were quoted at 5050 to 51 
per 100 pounds with some heavier weights ranging down to 46 and 
47 
a relatively low rate of hog slaughter this spring is expected 
to support prices the report said based on the size of last 
falls pig crop secondquarter slaughter could be down 7 percent 
from a year earlier the smallest for the spring quarter since 
1987 
most hogs grow to market weights in five to seven months so 
pigs farrowed in the fall usually make up most of the marketings in 
the second quarter 
the reduced supply of market hogs this spring could create 
difficulties for the packing industry the report said last 
year while hog producers were paring herds pork packers were 
expanding their slaughter capacity 
consequently the spread between hog prices and fresh pork 
prices narrowed in 1989 and these packer margins will narrow 
further through the first half of this year 
looking at cattle the report said choicegrade steers at omaha 
quoted at 7650 to 77 on monday may continue in the upper 
