<TEXT>
the senate debate over cleaning up the 
nations air is moving from behind closed doors to the senate floor 
with consideration of compromise legislation that is endorsed by 
the white house 
as the bill representing the first tightening of federal 
airpollution laws in 13 years came up for discussions late 
monday it promptly came under attack as being too expensive and 
burdensome to industry 
but senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine said he 
does not intend to see the legislation languish he called it the 
best package that could be fashioned in nearly three weeks of 
closeddoor talks with the bush administration 
were going to stay with this bill until we complete it 
sooner or later said mitchell he said congress has grappled 
with clean air legislation for a decade and rarely has there been 
legislation so thoroughly considered so long debated so much 
discussed 
the way for floor action was cleared last week when senate 
leaders and the white house agreed on curbs on toxic industrial 
chemicals released into the air smogcausing pollutants from 
automobiles and the compounds that cause acid rain 
its uncertain how long the debate over the compromise 
legislation might last sen bob dole rkan the minority leader 
last week urged mitchell to allow ample time for discussions and 
amendments that might be brought up 
after brief opening remarks by mitchell and several senators 
monday the discussions were recessed and were not expected to 
resume until later today 
but even before the revised legislation was brought to the 
floor the compromise came under attack from both critics who said 
it was too tough on industry and senators who called it too weak to 
clean the dirty skies over the nations cities 
sen steve symms ridaho who was the only member of the 
environment and public works committee to vote against an earlier 
version of the legislation last november said the compromise 
represented little improvement over the committee bill 
its the big long arm of the federal government intruding into 
the lives of the american people said symms im not sure we 
need this bill right now 
mitchell snapped back that symms has opposed every effort to 
improve the quality of americas air in the past 10 years 
at a news conference sen frank lautenberg dnj said the 
legislation fails to require the auto emission controls needed to 
clean the air in seriously polluted areas such as the major 
metropolitan areas of the northeast 
americans are choking on dirty air and the clean air bill 
coming to the senate floor just wont get the job done said 
lautenberg he promised to seek some changes to the bill in the 
coming days 
but the two floor managers of the bill sens max baucus 
dmont and john chafee rri said the bill represented a 
significant step forward in achieving cleaner air including new 
controls on sulfur dioxide emissions from power plant and other 
boilers a major precursor of acid rain 
among other provisions the bill calls for annual sulfur dioxide 
emissions to be cut by 10 million tons or a bit less than half by 
the year 2000 tougher auto tailpipe controls and new curbs on 
industrial pollution to reduce urban smog in urban areas and a 
requirement that industry use the best available technology to 
reduce toxic chemical releases 
while the legislation moves to floor debate in the senate a 
similar clean air bill remains in a house committee 
</TEXT>
