in a speech monday to the central committee of the ruling 
marxist workers party mengistu said he wants a return to 
capitalism 
the embattled president is fighting two bitter guerrilla wars 
simultaneously and facing cuts in aid from his principal 
benefactor the soviet union he appears to be wooing foreign 
investment 
the central committee must approve mengistus recommendations 
but there appeared to be little chance that it would not go along 
with his plans for a drastic overhaul of the countrys shattered 
economy 
in recent months mengistu has taken many small seemingly 
halfhearted steps to attract foreign investment and encourage 
domestic production but his speech monday appeared a near total 
capitulation to capitalism 
he conceded that economic central planning had been a failure 
among the specific reforms mengistu mentioned were 
allowing the private sector to take part in all sectors of the 
economy with no limit on capital investment ethiopia has had a 
250000 ceiling on all types of private investment 
giving governmentowned land on a concessional basis to 
private commercial firms for construction of industries hotels and 
a wide range of other enterprises 
allowing developers to build houses apartments and office 
buildings for rent or sale at present all land and commercial 
deeds are held by the government 
putting the governments myriad of stateowned industries and 
businesses on a profit basis with those continuing to lose money 
to be sold or closed 
