stiff desert winds slowed 
efforts to prepare space shuttle atlantis for a piggyback jet ride 
back to florida 
gusts to 45 mph also delayed an investigation into an apparent 
leak of hydraulic fluid discovered before the shuttle landed here 
sunday from a secret 4day mission during which it put a 500 
million spy satellite in orbit 
as far as the landing it was not a safety issue conrad 
nagel atlantis processing director for nasa said of the leak 
meanwhile discovery was towed monday to an assembly building at 
kennedy space center in florida nasa spokeswoman pat phillips said 
inside booster rockets and the external fuel tank will be 
attached to discovery which is scheduled for launch april 12 on a 
mission to put the 155 billion hubble space telescope in orbit 
atlantis was towed off its dry lakebed landing strip and into a 
100foot steel maintenance structure but the wind prevented nasa 
from hoisting the shuttle as planned monday morning slowing work 
by about 16 hours nagel said 
nagel said the delay forced officials to postpone the trip atop 
a modified boeing 747 to florida from friday to saturday 
the possible leak of bright red hydraulic fluid was discovered 
as atlantis approached landing sensors showed a brief pressure 
drop in the main hydraulic system 
the system operates control surfaces that steer the spacecraft 
under computer orders during reentry nagel said 
overall he said the shuttle was in excellent condition only 
one heatshield tile may need replacement about 20 other tiles 
sustained dings up to an inch in size while about 40 others 
had nicks of a half inch or less 
