<TEXT>
the uncertainties looming ahead with the 
prospect of german reunification have given east germans cold feet 
and touched off a new political crisis in west germany 
east germanys leading politicians on monday called for a new 
social charter to be adopted in both germanys that would preserve 
the protections they have enjoyed under socialism like guaranteed 
employment and affordable rent and food prices 
the proposed social charter adopted at weekly negotiations 
between the communists and 15 other parties reflects just how 
hesitant many east germans are about plunging ahead with a merger 
with capitalist west germany and abandoning the life theyve known 
for 40 years 
in bonn chancellor helmut kohl fueled the controversy raging 
over his refusal to unequivocally recognize germanys border with 
poland 
he told reporters monday that germans should be wary of polands 
1953 pledge not to seek world war ii reparations contending polish 
officials have been pressing claims for the past three years for 
compensation of forced labor by poles under the third reich 
but kohl backed off the reparations issue today his chief of 
staff rudolf seiters said kohl agreed to formally state support 
for a treaty on polands western border without asking for 
concessions from the poles 
the announcement followed a crucial meeting of kohls coalition 
government which has been seriously divided over the chancellors 
handling of the border issue 
seiters said the coalition partners agreed to introduce a 
resolution in parliament thursday favoring a treaty recognizing the 
current borders with poland 
it was not clear whether the resolution would state as kohl 
has many times insisted that only the government of a united 
germany can have final say on the border issue 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki of poland has called on the 
two germanys to begin talks aimed at a treaty recognizing the 
current border formed by the oder and neisse rivers as the 
permanent boundary between poland and a united germany 
about a third of modernday poland was german territory prior to 
world war ii and warsaw fears a united germany might seek to 
recover the regions 
the chancellors obstinance angered poles opposition social 
democrats in west germany the world war ii allies who retain 
control of berlin and even members of his own centerright 
coalition government 
foreign minister hansdietrich genscher had distanced himself 
from kohl on the border issue and warned him that reopening the 
issue of war reparations for poland could backfire 
kohls conservative christian democratic union governs in 
partnership with genschers liberal free democrats and with the 
archconservative christian social union of bavaria 
the christian social unions chairman theo waigel last year 
called for unification within the 1937 borders of germany which 
would include the huge territorities of silesia and east prussia 
lost to poland and the soviet union after the nazi defeat in 1945 
the christian democrats and free democrats also appear to be at 
odds over how unification should be accomplished with kohls party 
urging a unilateral decision by east german states to merge with 
west germany 
a leading parliamentarian of the free democratic party burkhard 
hirsch contends no right of secession exists for that east german 
states 
the opposition social democrats oppose an immediate vote by a 
newly seated east german parliament to merge with west germany 
calling instead for a convention to draft a joint constitution 
the social charter adopted at the east german political talks 
demands that the right to work and the right to housing be 
enshrined in a new constitution for a united germany 
if adopted by the east german parliament chosen in the march 18 
election the charter should serve as the basis for negotiations 
with west germany on monetary and social union opposition minister 
gerhard poppe said 
the charter proposal illustrates the strong social democratic 
leaning of east germanys political forces the countrys social 
democrats are expected to poll a majority in the election 
east germans have traditionally viewed their social security 
programs as the paramount achievement of over 40 years of communist 
rule and are nervous about the prospects of a headlong plunge into 
capitalisms cold waters 
once efficient western methods are introduced to east germanys 
governmentcontrolled industry for example the nownegligible 
unemployment rate among the countrys 9 millionstrong workforce 
could jump to as much as 15 percent rent prices are also likely to 
surge 
east germans in general know little about west germanys social 
security system viewed as one of western europes most generous 
the conservative alliance for germany the east german political 
grouping backed by kohls christian democratic union has appealed 
to voters not to fear the switch to capitalism 
social minister norbert bluem of west germany appeared at a news 
conference with leaders of the east german christian democrats and 
noted that the bonn government already spends about 410 billion 
per year on social services or more than 6500 per capita 
</TEXT>
