<TEXT>
two new supreme court rulings will make it 
much more difficult for convicted criminals including many of the 
nations 2200 death row inmates to get help in federal courts 
the rulings generally bar defendants from invoking new 
constitutional decisions to attack their state court convictions 
after they have exhausted their initial round of appeals 
that means prisoners may not base their appeals on favorable 
court rulings issued in other cases after their own convictions 
become final in state appellate courts 
by identical 54 splits the court monday upheld death sentences 
for two men on death row in south carolina and oklahoma 
in each case the courts conservative bloc chief justice 
william h rehnquist and justices byron r white sandra day 
oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy joined to form 
the majority 
in each the courts liberals justices william j brennan 
thurgood marshall harry a blackmun and john paul stevens 
dissented 
the courts new and stringent rule was announced in the case of 
south carolina death row inmate horace butler it evoked a sharp 
dissenting opinion by brennan 
after today he wrote for the four dissenters despite 
constitutional defects in the state process leading to their 
conviction or sentencing state prisoners will languish in jail 
or others like butler will die because state courts were 
reasonable even though wrong 
brennan said that with the ruling in butlers case the court 
has finally succeeded in its thinly veiled crusade to eviscerate 
federal laws passed by congress to protect criminal defendants 
rights 
writing for the majority rehnquist said federal courts should 
not review reasonable goodfaith interpretations of existing 
precedents made by state courts even though they are shown to be 
contrary to later decisions 
in the oklahoma case of robyn leroy parks the court said he is 
barred from contending that a jury wrongly was told to ignore 
sympathy before it sentenced him to death 
the court said parks should not have been allowed to raise such 
a constitutional argument in a federal court challenge after having 
exhausted his direct appeals in state courts 
the presiding judge told parks sentencing jury you must 
avoid any influence of sympathy sentiment passion prejudice or 
other arbitrary factor when imposing sentence 
the justices left unanswered whether such a jury instruction is 
constitutional 
in another death penalty ruling the court struck down a key 
portion of north carolinas death penalty law invalidating the 
death sentences of most of the states 84 death row inmates 
and in a separate decision the court upheld a california 
killers death sentence by ruling that the instructions given to 
