the successor to the nowdissolved polish 
communist party is ready to turn over to warsaw university the 
massive building that was party headquarters for four decades 
the imposing building in central warsaw derisively dubbed the 
white house has been at the heart of a nationwide debate over 
regaining for the state treasury the vast holdings accumulated by 
the communists when they controlled the government 
during a weekend meeting the social democracy party which 
inherited the assets of the communist party when it disbanded in 
january agreed to hand over the central committee headquarters to 
a government commission with the recommendation it be given to the 
university said marek siwiec 
i dont have to hide our great joy said wlodzimierz 
siwinski deputy rector of the university which plans to use the 
building as a library 
the social democracy partys supreme council made the decision 
saturday and representatives met sunday with the commission 
established by the solidarityled government to review the legal 
status of communist party property the turnover of the building 
must be approved by all sides 
many of those who supported erection of the building wrote or 
called us demanding that it should remain in the hands of the 
polish left wing said siwiec editor of the social democracy 
newspaper trybuna 
but we hope that the needs of culture and science will get 
dominating respect and the building will go to the university 
siwiec said 
since the east blocs first noncommunistled government took 
power last fall the communists have been under intense pressure to 
return property no longer supported by membership or power 
on monday general secretary leszek miller reported the social 
democracy party had signed up 47000 members and said he was 
satisfied with its growth the communist party claimed a membership 
of 2 million 
