<TEXT>
facing international pressure 
to reopen palestinian universities israels army on tuesday 
allowed classes to resume at a west bank teachers college 
the peaceful resumption of classes at the arub academy and the 
planned reopening of other twoyear schools were seen as tests for 
a possible restart of universities that have been shut almost since 
the start of the 26monthold palestinian uprising 
but the army said soldiers closed two elementary schools and a 
middle school tuesday in the west bank city of nablus raising to 
27 the number of primary and secondary schools shut so far this 
year for disturbances 
arab education officials were told the latest closures were 
because pupils had stoned west bank military commander yitzhak 
mordechais military jeep 
the arub academy a mens college that trains students to teach 
english arabic islamic studies and geography was the scene of 
jubilant reunions tuesday with students kissing each other on the 
cheeks in a traditional arab greeting 
its one of the happiest days we have had said hamad 
sarsur the headmaster 
hurrying for class with a notebook in hand yousef asafreh said 
that because of army closures he has spent more than four years 
trying to get a teaching certificate in arabic that normally takes 
two years 
he and other students said the hillside campus located near the 
arub refugee camp on the road to hebron would not be used for 
political protests 
it is our central demand that we be educated said asafreh 
25 students understand that they cannot receive education with 
riots riots and education cannot go together 
arub had 82 students and 12 teachers before the uprising began 
in december 1987 but only 55 students showed up for class tuesday 
sarsur said he did not yet know if any students were in jail for 
antiisraeli activism 
he predicted unrest would not start on the arub campus adding 
the students are eager to return to their desks 
army officials said if there was no trouble at the arub college 
where classes were held peacefully tuesday then officials would 
open the other 15 community colleges 
it is going to be gradual said one official who demanded 
anonymity if there is no incitement or security violations we 
will see all of them open and functioning in a short time 
he and other officials declined to make specific pledges but 
suggested a peaceful reopening of junior colleges would pave the 
way for universities to resume operation 
the army has kept six palestinian universities with about 21000 
students and 16 junior colleges and vocational schools with about 
5000 students shut for 26 months 
officials say the campuses are potential rallying points for 
antiisraeli violence but palestinians contend the closures are an 
unjustified collective punishment 
a leaflet issued by the proplo underground leadership of the 
uprising tuesday called for rallies near college campuses saturday 
to demand the opening of universities and the freeing of jailed 
students 
israel is being urged by european countries and the united 
states to allow universities to resume in january the european 
parliament imposed a freeze on scientific cooperation with israel 
until the universities were reopened 
there was also a call by the israeli parliaments education 
committee to open one campus to test whether it was safe to resume 
classes at other institutions 
elsewhere police spokesman mordechai bareket said a 35yearold 
arab woman who had a police record as a prostitute and drug addict 
was killed in hebron her body was found in the yard of her house 
with the head smashed and bloodied 
arab reports described her as a collaborator with israeli 
authorities but police said she was not known as a collaborator 
the death brought to 192 the number of palestinians killed by 
fellow arabs during the uprising most for alleged collaboration or 
drug involvement some 659 palestinians have been killed by 
israelis and 43 israelis have also died 
in nablus the army used bulldozers to destroy the home of 
mohammed hawwash whose son jaber 20 was arrested last nov 8 and 
charged with being a member of the red eagles an underground group 
blamed for killing alleged collaborators six people lived in the 
threeroom house 
also tuesday the uprising leaders issued an order allowing 
stores in the occupied territories and arab east jerusalem to open 
for five hours daily adding two hours to the schedule shops have 
kept for most of the uprising 
a leaflet announced the move which marked the first easing of 
the strict discipline that the rebellions leaders have tried to 
maintain on palestinians 
