he said is happy to argue against increased social spending by 
pointing to the size of the deficit 
the administration while saying its proposing no tax increase 
is asking congress to vote an additional 157 billion in new 
revenues for the budget year that begins oct 1 after subtracting 
18 billion worth of targeted tax reductions that would leave a 
net revenue gain of 139 billion 
those proposals range from raising the tax on airline tickets to 
requiring all state and local government employees to pay for 
social security hospitalization coverage 
bentsen told gideon that congressional authorities say bushs 
proposals would cut the deficit by only 94 billion not 139 
billion there is no way to raise 139 billion without raising 
taxes bentsen said 
gideon spent a good deal of his time at the hearing defending 
bushs proposal to cut taxes on capital gains which are profits 
from the sale of investments the administration contends a 
reduction would provide such an incentive to the economy that it 
would increase tax collections 
congressional leaders reject that point their analysts say the 
capitalgains cut would lose 114 billion over five years 
however the treasury department says it would gain 125 
billion a difference of 239 billion 
