immigration arguing the measure hurt israels image and violated 
press freedom 
their protest came a day after us state department spokeswoman 
margaret tutwiler urged prime minister yitzhak shamir to reconsider 
the censorship order he issued friday 
the order which prohibited publication of how many immigrants 
arrived in february was announced last week after officials 
predicted up to 230000 soviets would arrive this year 
israeli officials said the restrictions that barred publication 
of figures and travel routes taken by soviet immigrants were needed 
for security reasons they cited recent arab protests about the 
influx and fears that immigrants might be attacked 
the army censor routinely reviews articles pertaining to 
military affairs before publication but coverage of immigration 
has rarely been applied 
editors and legal experts protested in newspaper editorials 
saying israeli leaders not journalists were to blame for the arab 
anger that followed shamirs suggestion israel needed occupied land 
to settle soviet immigrants 
moshe vardi editor of the masscirculation yediot ahronot 
daily accused the government of tarnishing israels image at a 
time when antidemocratic measures were increasingly unpopular 
in the free world and even beyond censorship is simply an 
incomprehensible term in 1990 it is a vestige of the past he 
wrote 
vardi and other editors sought a meeting with shamir they urged 
the government to seek an understanding with editors rather than 
impose blanket censorship on the soviet immigration story 
such an unwritten agreement existed during the 1984 airlift of 
ethiopian jews when selfcensorship kept the story secret for 
months 
