<TEXT>
japan successfully tested one of the worlds most 
advanced rocket engines tuesday and officials said the engine will 
have the capability to launch large sophisticated satellites 
the le7 engine burned normally during a foursecond firing 
test the national space development agency said the sophisticated 
engine is to power the first stage of a new japanese rocket the 
h2 on which japan has pinned many of its hopes for future space 
exploration 
the current mainstay of the japanese space program the h1 
rocket can lift only 1210 pounds into geostationary orbit making 
it incapable of launching large sophisticated communications 
satellites 
development of the japanesedesigned h2 also will also free 
japan from us veto power over commercial launches of 
thirdcountry satellites imposed as a licensing condition for us 
technology used in previous japanese rockets 
the h2 is slated to go into service in march 1992 and will 
match the twoton geostationary payload capabilities of current 
us soviet and european rockets 
the le7 engine powered by liquid hydrogen and oxygen uses a 
hightechnology propulsion system similar to that on the us space 
shuttle 
tuesdays success followed a string of development problems that 
technicians attributed to the extremely high stresses inside the 
highperformance engine 
the first stage of the current h1 rocket is based on 
25yearold us delta rocket technology licensed from mcdonnell 
douglas but the second stage is designed in japan and also will be 
used as the second stage of the h2 
mcdonnell douglas officials recently asked mitsubishi heavy 
industries to supply it with the new second stage to update the 
delta rocket japanese officials say 
on feb 22 a european ariane 44l rocket carrying two japanese 
communications satellites exploded shortly after liftoff 
destroying both satellites reportedly worth 600 million analysts 
say the accident is likely to further encourage japan to develop 
its own space capabilities 
despite a late start due in part to a postworld war ii ban by 
us occupation authorities and low budgets japans space program 
has progressed steadily and achieved an enviable success record 
a japanese satellite musesa is due to reach the moon on march 
18 making japan the third nation after the soviet union and the 
united states to reach earths closest neighbor 
</TEXT>
