<TEXT>
the pentagon increased its stockpile of 
unrequired spare parts and supplies by 4 billion over three years 
creating a system that is like opening the door to imelda marcos 
closet a lawmaker said tuesday 
the general accounting office released three reports describing 
widespread problems in the defense departments management of its 
103 billion supply system including excessive purchases of 
unnecessary items and storage space devoted to obsolete items 
officials from the gao the investigative arm of congress told 
the senate governmental affairs committee that in 1987 the 
department had a 30 billion inventory of unrequired items three 
years later the stockpile costs 34 billion 
the gao said it based its report on pentagon estimates 
although we found no dominant reason that caused inventory 
growth we believe the growth results from a tendency to stock far 
into the future said frank c conahan assistant comptroller 
general this is fostered by a management philosophy that rewards 
obligating funds and filling orders 
