the government of chad continues to detain torture 
and summarily execute political prisoners despite the adoption of a 
new constitution guaranteeing human rights amnesty international 
said wednesday 
president hissene habre has direct knowledge of some of the 
abuses and many of the several hundred political detainees had 
been held within 50 yards of the presidential office the human 
rights organization said 
chad has been a catalogue of horror since habre gained power 
in 1982 said amnesty international representative jamal benomar 
speaking at a news conference tuesday he said habres government 
had refused to respond to amnesty internationals allegations and 
refused to disclose any information about the fate of political 
prisoners 
the authorities have never admitted that these detainees 
exist benomar said 
according to the amnesty international report some prisoners 
were arbitrarily detained because they belonged to a particular 
ethnic group suspected of antigovernment activities others were 
detained solely because of relatives activities the report said 
in december the government adopted a new constitution that 
guarantees basic individual rights as well as freedom of speech 
and assembly but amnesty international said there had been no 
perceptible change in the governments treatment of political 
prisoners 
benomar said torture of political prisoners in chad has become 
routine with increasing use of electric shocks women prisoners 
have been forced by soldiers to serve as slaves and prostitutes 
the report said 
prisoners are held incommunicado and denied medical 
attention the report said no one sees the detainees except 
the security personnel guarding and interrogating them 
habre became president in 1982 after driving a libyanbacked 
rival out of the capital ndjamena during a civil war in 
december his government claimed voters in a referendum gave 
overwhelming approval to the new constitution and to a new 
sevenyear term for habre 
he said the election introduced chad to an era of democracy 
but has allowed no opposition political activity 
benomar said some opponents of the government have crossed the 
border into sudan and are taking up arms against habre 
