the opposition will have access to state 
broadcast media during election campaigns the national assembly 
announced tuesday amid preparations for the first free balloting 
in more than four decades 
lawmakers adopted a new statute for radio and television which 
is responsible to the legislature and no longer to the government 
but it was unclear whether the measure would grant the broadcast 
media more independence 
in a marked departure from the past when state radio and 
television reflected the official view the statute specified 
commentaries on radio and television represent the personal 
opinion of the commentators 
communists in bulgaria unlike those in other soviet bloc 
countries have retained much of their clout in national politics 
legislative elections are scheduled for june the first after 45 
years of hardline communist rule 
the duration of the election messages and other details were to 
be included in an electoral law which was among key legislation 
held up by the suspension on feb 12 of talks between the ruling 
communists and the opposition the talks broke down over the 
communists refusal to agree on key political reforms 
on monday the legislature enacted a law restoring the names of 
the 15 million ethnic turks and other moslems forced to adopt 
bulgarian names in an assimilation campaign authored by the 
communists 
legislators said the media statute was modeled after similar 
legislation in several west european countries it stipulates that 
radio and television must be objective they must not serve one 
party or group 
according to the new law the broadcast media will be controlled 
by a committee of eight legislators and seven other leaders 
the heads of state radio and television will be proposed by the 
