<TEXT>
here is a summary of the key provisions of the 
compromise clean air bill being considered by the senate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
local communities must attain federal air quality standards 
within five 10 or 15 years depending on the severity of the 
problem the los angeles area is allowed 20 years 
areas must show annual progress ozone reductions of 4 percent 
a year for the first six years and 3 percent annually thereafter a 
waiver may be granted if the costs of the annual reductions exceed 
5000 per ton of ozoneforming pollutants 
reductions are to be attained through cuts in automobile 
emissions and smogcausing releases from industrial plants small 
business emitting less than 100 tons are exempt 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
automakers must reduce tailpipe emissions of smogcausing 
pollutants with all cars covered by new emission controls by 1995 
hydrocarbons unburned fuel would have to be cut by 22 percent 
to 025 grams per mile and nitrogen oxides by 60 percent to 04 
grams 
a second round of tailpipe controls would go into effect in 2003 
cutting emissions another 50 percent if 11 cities now with 
serious pollution problems fail to meet air quality standards 
cities with even more serious problems would have to use 
cleanerburning fuels such as methanol or specially formulated 
gasoline 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
utilities must reduce in two phases annual sulfur dioxide 
emissions by 10 million tons by the year 2000 and cap emissions at 
1980 levels at that time first phase begins in 1995 but utilities 
using clean coal technology may delay initial compliance until 1997 
dirty plants primarily in the midwest also received extra 
pollution control allowances which may be sold to recoup some of 
control costs western states also receive additional bonus 
allowances to provide cushion for growth 
nitrogen oxide emissions by utilities must be reduced 4 million 
tons by year 2005 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
industry must install by 1997 the best available technology 
to reduce releases of 191 toxic chemicals by up to 90 percent 
the national academy of sciences will recommend methods for 
assessing remaining health risks especially from cancer the 
environmental protection agency must implement healthbased 
standards to deal with those risks after study is completed 
</TEXT>
