<TEXT>
parliament on tuesday adopted a labor law 
that recognizes the right to strike for the first time in east 
germanys 40year history while forbidding employers from locking 
out workers 
the embrace of one capitalist tactic and rejection of another 
highlights the indecision gripping east germans as they begin 
considering how to merge their nation with west germany 
members of parliament praised the new labor code that mixes 
marketstyle reforms with traditional socialist protections but 
conceded it probably will stir protest among west german investors 
and employers eyeing unification 
the labor law easily won approval from the 385 lawmakers present 
for what is expected to be the last session of the 500member 
peoples chamber prior to the nations first competitive elections 
on march 18 only six voted against the measure with 53 
abstentions debate was minimal 
the future of the new labor law may rest with the new 
400member parliament many labor principles embodied in the law 
require implementing legislation that will have to be tackled after 
the new legislative body is seated 
the strike clause however is among changes to take effect next 
week 
lawmakers hailed the nolockout clause as a workers right not 
enjoyed in west germany 
because the law is likely to be seen as imbalanced by west 
german industries seeking to build plants or engage in joint 
production operations in east germany it may serve to slow the 
investment considered essential to turning around the flagging 
economy 
the law comes in the form of a constitutional change it permits 
unions to call strikes if arbitration fails to resolve 
labormanagement differences in negotiations 
strikes have been forbidden in east germany and most socialist 
states labor unions traditionally were powerless to challenge 
policies handed down by communist authorities who dominated all 
social and economic matters until last fall 
the government now will have the right to intercede and stop a 
strike only if the walkout is deemed a threat to public wellbeing 
the law provides that no one can reduce or hinder unions in 
their rightful occupation 
communist lawmaker kaethe niederkirchner said such a broad 
protection was likely to disturb the capitalists next door he 
quoted west german employers association president klaus murmann as 
describing the law as a hindrance to intergerman economic 
cooperation 
parliament also adopted additional measures on election 
procedures including extending voting rights to foreigners who 
have lived in east germany for two years or more 
</TEXT>
