<TEXT>
a romanian exile leader told prime minister 
margaret thatcher and members of parliament tuesday that chances of 
free elections in romania are nil because communists control the 
government media and economy 
ion ratiu said the national salvation front has taken over the 
old communist party structure and is using it to help win the may 
20 general election the front took power in the december 
revolution that toppled communist dictator nicolae ceausescu 
ratiu 72 who arrived from bucharest tuesday and planned to 
return wednesday is president of the world union of free 
romanians he was granted asylum in britain in 1940 and became a 
wealthy businessman he now hopes to run for parliament in romania 
as a candidate of the national peasants party the largest 
opposition group 
after meeting mrs thatcher he told an allparty meeting at the 
house of commons that the western news media and western embassies 
in romania were perpetuating the view that the opposition parties 
are incapable of producing a coherent government 
ratiu said many of the 47 political parties formed since the 
revolution are phantom parties subservient to the front 
he said that nonetheless if free and unfettered elections were 
held and the result was a plurality for the opposition a coalition 
of nonfront parties would form a government that is very 
credible and very capable 
ratiu said he doubted there will be free elections 
in the country at large the entire structure of the 
communist party with small exceptions is now active as the front 
the chances of free fair and unfettered elections are nil under 
these circumstances he said 
effectively the front still has control of the media economy 
and the government infrastructure and all its members have a vested 
selfinterest in victory for the front party 
ratiu chided french president francois mitterrand and premier 
michel rocard for receiving prime minister petre roman and not 
arranging a single ministerial meeting for corneliu coposu 
president of the peasants party who has been in paris this week 
i do not wish to see the front recognized as a legitimate 
government he said 
ratiu said romanias interim president ion iliescu agreed last 
week to allow the world union of free romanians to publish an 
independent newspaper and new radio and television stations 
a printing press will be delivered next week and ratiu said he 
expects to start publication in two weeks equipment for the tv 
channel is in bucharest and we can start it at once within two 
days he said 
he said the exile group would send 100 tons of paper to romania 
for the election campaign and it would be offered equally to all 
parties including the front 
</TEXT>
