all nations in the former soviet bloc 
except romania will have trade agreements with the european 
community by the end of april a senior official of the community 
said tuesday 
frans andriessen commissioner for trade and foreign affairs 
said accords with east germany bulgaria and czechoslovakia would 
be concluded before the ec summit on eastern europe is held april 
28 in dublin ireland 
agreements were signed in 1988 and 1989 with hungary poland and 
the soviet union the scope of an agreement czechoslovakia signed 
in 1988 is being widened 
andriessen said the first generation agreements would be a 
basis for more extensive commercial relations he said a pact could 
not be signed with romania because its government was more of a 
caretaker administration than the others 
second generation agreements to be negotiated later are 
intended to be a model we can use for the construction of a 
greater europe andriessen said 
the official said those agreements would deal with establishing 
a free trade zone political cooperation common projects in 
sectors such as transport and the environment and financial deals 
like a 12 billion loan arranged for hungary 
