<DOCNO> AP900306-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the air force is paying for a 100000 
study to determine how lowflying f4 phantom fighter jets may 
affect the health and behavior of pregnant horses kept near 
military bases 
simulated bursts of jet noise will reverberate through barns for 
nine months to determine their effect on eight pregnant 
thoroughbred and saddlebred horses researchers at the university 
of florida said monday 
another control group of eight pregnant mares will not be 
exposed to the flyover din 
heavily pregnant mares may be more susceptible to the stress 
of aircraft noise said dr michelle leblanc a veterinarian 
one of the common complaints the air force receives is that 
abortions seem to occur more often in mares subjected to lowflying 
aircraft 
leblanc associate professor at the university of floridas 
department of large animal clinical sciences said about 50 studies 
on the effects of aircraft noise on animals have been conducted 
since the arrival of sonic boom in the 1950s 
but because many studies werent considered scientifically 
valid the air force sought additional research with domestic 
animals she said 
the study is funded by the air forces unit of noise and sonic 
boom impact technology she said 
the reason for the research on domestic animals is to provide 
data on general and potential damage claims incurred by the air 
force as a result of farm or ranch overflights said maj michael 
thompson project manager of air force studies on sonic booms 
leblanc said stress may affect the quantity and quality of 
antibodies produced in the mares first milk or the ability of 
foals to absorb the antibodies 
foals rely on these antibodies for protection against 
infectious diseases during the first few weeks of life and theyre 
only capable of absorbing these antibodies during their first 18 
hours of life she said 
each randomly timed noise burst will last three seconds 
increasing about 50 decibels per second until it peaks at 120 
decibels comparable to the noise of a jackhammer she said 
ultrasound will be used in monitoring the horses heart activity 
and fetal movement while video cameras record behavioral reactions 
to the sounds 
leblanc aims to pinpoint the threshold of noise that prompts a 
frightened horse to bolt the air force could use that information 
to determine when their aircraft should fly higher to diffuse the 
noise she said 
the horses in the study might get a little upset over the jet 
sounds at first but they should adjust to it quickly leblanc 
said 
next year with the help of real air force jets leblanc will 
continue the study using authentic flyover experiments she said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

