<TEXT>
human testing of a potential aids 
vaccine was approved monday by state health officials but 
researchers cautioned that development of a true vaccine will take 
years 
the approval was the first for human trials of hgp30 in the 
united states according to the companies that developed the drug 
clinical trials will be held at san francisco general hospital 
and the university of southern california medical center in los 
angeles said dr james kahn who will conduct the san francisco 
tests the trials will begin in two to three months he said 
this is just a very preliminary stage said kahn who called 
hgp30 a candidate vaccine its the first step but its not 
something thats going to cure aids and it is not intended as a 
cure or treatment for aids 
the trials were approved by the state department of health 
services food and drug branch said tom hazlet of the branch 
in the tests 24 healthy people who test negative for human 
immunodeficiency virus or hiv which causes aids will receive 
escalating doses of hgp30 and be monitored for at least a year 
doctors will try to determine the vaccines toxicity and see if 
it causes the body to produce antibodies to the virus kahn said 
another potential vaccine for the incurable disease is being 
tested at the national cancer institute in washington dc kahn 
said 
experts in the field say tests of a potential vaccine for an 
aidslike disease in monkeys also shows promise for the development 
of a treatment that could prevent aids in humans 
hgp30 targets for destruction a core protein of hiv the 
vaccine is designed to trigger antibodies to the protein which is 
found in all strains of the aids virus according to alpha 1 
biomedical inc of washington and celsci corp of alexandria va 
which developed the vaccine 
hgp30 is the first potential vaccine to be tested in humans 
where the active component is a completely synthetic molecule the 
companies said in a news release 
because the vaccine lacks live or dead virus there is no chance 
that hgp30 could cause aids infection the companies said 
kahn assistant professor of medicine at the university of 
californiasan francisco and a member of the aidsoncology division 
at the universityaffiliated san francisco general said most 
researchers believe it will be five to 10 years before an effective 
aids vaccine is developed 
by the end of last month the federal centers for disease 
control in atlanta had recorded a cumulative total of 121645 cases 
of aids in the united states with 72580 deaths or 60 percent of 
all cases 
</TEXT>
