<TEXT>
the internal revenue service has served summonses on criminal 
defense attorneys around the country demanding that they reveal the 
names of clients who paid large lawyer fees with cash an irs 
official confirmed tuesday 
lawyers argue that such disclosures would violate the 
fundamental right of attorneyclient privilege 
the attorneys were told to bring their financial records to irs 
offices according to miami attorney neal sonnett president of the 
national association of criminal defense lawyers one lawyer served 
said an irs agent told him that 900 lawyers were to receive 
summonses 
we have heard from enough lawyers around the country to 
recognize that it appears to be a nationwide assault upon criminal 
defense lawyers said sonnett whose organization knows of 12 
lawyers who were served i think theres hundreds of 
attorneys who will go to jail for this 
in october the irs sent letters to about 940 criminal defense 
attorneys requesting information on clients who paid them more than 
10000 in cash sonnett said 
the letter signed by christopher j lezovich an irs official 
in detroit was sent to attorneys around the country giving them 30 
days to identify the clients it also included a warning that 
noncompliance would result in summonses 
tax collectors are acting under a disclosure law passed by 
congress in 1985 the law initially widely ignored was aimed at 
exposing tax evaders including major drug dealers who often 
transact business in cash 
the original penalties for failure to disclose were only 
misdemeanors but a year ago congress reclassified violations as 
felonies punishable by up to 10 years in prison 
the summonses received by lawyers on tuesday were signed by 
local irs agents sonnett said 
lezovich said tuesday night that the detroit irs office within 
the past 10 days wrote to field offices to advise them that agents 
might want to serve summonses against the lawyers who received the 
letters in october 
we got some back some provided the information some didnt 
of those some were selected for the first wave of summonses he 
said the detroit irs office is one of the agencys main computer 
centers and it processes form 8300 which among other things 
requests that filers list cash sums of at least 10000 they have 
received 
we anticipate that was just a first cut this isnt going to 
be the end of it lezovich said of the summonses 
justice department spokesman david runkel said his department 
took part in discussions last year with the irs and lawyers groups 
on the issue 
its very clear what the issue is here it grows out of 
concerns about drug payments runkel said 
sonnett said the summonses request that attorneys bring all 
their financial records including bank statements and payment 
records and not just bookkeeping related to the federal 8300 forms 
i cannot conceive of a summons that is more blatantly a 
fishing expedition which in effect asks the lawyer to turn over 
all his financial records to the irs to roam through he said 
john wesley hall a criminal defense lawyer in little rock said 
revenue agent john w prather jr of little rock indicated that a 
nationwide move by the irs was under way against 900 lawyers who 
refused to reveal the names of clients 
hall said he would not comply with the demand of the summons 
the summons served on hall directed him to bring all his bank 
records from 1987 to 1989 to the irs office in little rock on march 
27 
talk about overreaching hall said adding that he has had 
two clients pay him more than 10000 each during the last three 
years the summons involves one of them he said 
the privilege of the lawyerclient relationship is not only 
granted in state law but also is a constitutional privilege hall 
said 
i believe i am dutybound not to provide the requested 
information hall said 
