entrepreneur chris graff wants the world to 
know he can build a better bedframe but his trademarked 
bedfellows at first glance a collection of oddly twisted metal 
tubes doesnt look like a bedframe 
he believes thats his problem 
graff finds that largely indifferent manufacturers sales reps 
and customers are suggesting he give the idea a rest the path to 
his office door at geste corp hasnt been beaten smooth 
its been pretty cold all across the board he says 
so it often goes when inventors and business venturers attempt 
to sell the public a new twist on an old idea say patent attorneys 
and marketing experts 
customers are reluctant to change marketers are slow to see the 
new products brilliance at least from the inventors point of 
view those whose fortunes are tied to conventional products may 
battle the upstart competition 
with a lot of innovative products regardless of their 
performance and the benefits they provide that is the wall the 
innovator keeps running up against says scott jessup who 
teaches entrepreneurship at the university of notre dame 
in the world of sponsored research each patentable idea may 
cost at least 5 million purdue university figures show a 
corporate portfolio containing hundreds of patents may include only 
a few that actually make money 
its tough for the big fish and even harder for the small fry 
more than 40 years ago preston tucker introduced an automobile 
that bore his name and offered motorists a fourdoor fastback with 
a rear engine and headlights that turned with the steering wheel 
only 51 cars were produced and tuckers dream died mired in 
securities and exchange commission fraud charges that ended in an 
acquittal 
