<TEXT>
 
la gioconda opera in four acts by amilcare ponchielli a 
three cd album cbs records 
 
what is one to make of la gioconda anyway its a 
warhorse in the worst sense of the term a clunky work with an 
absurd plot cardboard characters and some long strecthes of 
thirdrate music yet its big tunes are winners and given a strong 
recording such as this one the opera should win over plenty of 
listeners to its crude but forceful charms 
as the album notes by barrymore laurence scherer point out this 
relic is about the only surviving specimen of italian opera from 
the long period when verdi late in life temporarily retired from 
composing for the stage that would span the period between 
aida in 1871 and otello in 1887 gioconda premiered at 
la scala in 1876 
the title role of the anythingbuthappy street singer is 
powerfully sung here by eva marton like ghena dimitrova who sang 
the role at the metropolitan opera this year she exemplifies the 
stentorian rather than the lyric school of soprano singing 
thats fine since subtlety seems beside the point in portraying a 
character who from the moment the curtain rises barely stops 
rushing from one crisis to another in act 1 she frets that her 
blind mother will be burned at the stake in act 2 she tries to 
murder her romantic rival in act 3 she turns around and saves the 
rivals life in act 4 she finally stabs herself to avoid the 
sexual advances of the villain 
as enzo the noblemanindisguise whom gioconda loves tenor 
giorgio lamberti is no pavarotti but he sounds at least decent 
and better than that in his big act 2 aria cielo e mar 
baritone sherrill milnes enthusiastically throws what remains of 
his once impressive voice into the role of the evil barnaba but he 
cant avoid sounding frayed and occasionally flat 
mezzo livia budai is imposing as laura contralto anne gjevang 
does nicely by the lovely act 1 prayer ponchielli composed for la 
cieca giocondas mother and bass samuel ramey is wasted in the 
silly and entirely uninteresting part of alvise 
the late giuseppe patane conducts the hungarian state orchestra 
with the verve and smoothness for which he was renowned 
by mike silverman associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
jeff becks guitar shop epic jeff beck 
 
its tough these days being a guitar hero every heavy metal 
band has at least one leaving few riffs unturned 
how can a guy attract some attention with so much competition 
jeff beck who first won fame as a guitar pyrotechnician in the 
1960s decided to make studio gadgetry the cornerstone of the 
mostly instrumental jeff becks guitar shop 
bad idea the result is hightech but nosoul this music 
contains a little rock a little jazz and a lot of microchips 
beck filters his guitar through every gizmo money can buy and 
he jumps from one timbre to another for no good reason the 
synthesizers of tony hymas only reinforce the cold 21st century 
ambience 
the music works best when beck settles on one setting and just 
plays which he does a few times the slow where were you 
features a pretty melody but ends abruptly sling shot is 
propelled by reckless scorching licks and day in the house 
offers a great guitar break and even a political point of view in 
concise terms 
but most of the rest is beck dreck nothing here approaches his 
fine 70s fusion albums blow by blow and wired or his 
more recent gorgeous work on rod stewarts cover of people get 
ready beck would do well to pay less attention to knobs and 
levels and more attention to melody and rhythm 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
