<TEXT>
art patrons battling red ink and bad press 
over an exhibit of priceless imperial chinese art believe the 
investment in prestige and tourism potential was worth the loss of 
millions of private and public dollars 
the son of heaven imperial arts of china exhibit attracted 
500000 visitors during a fivemonth stint in seattle in 1988 and 
672000 during its eightmonth show in columbus last year it was 
the largest exhibition of historic chinese art and artifacts ever 
seen in the united states 
the show which opened here last march and closed in september 
featured objects from the palaces of chinese emperors and kings who 
collectively ruled over a 2600year period the works were 
primarily lent by museums in beijing and eight chinese provinces 
the pieces included lifesize terracotta horses and warrior 
sculptures from the tomb of chinas first emperor 2500yearold 
cooking vessels and temple bells delicate scroll paintings from 
the 15th century and a 2nd century jade burial suit 
some of the items were found in recent archeological digs in 
china son of heaven was chinas term for its emperors 
believed to be the human link to heaven 
unequivocally yes it was worth it to use a sports analogy 
maybe the score didnt come out quite like we thought and maybe the 
plays werent executed precisely as wed hoped but we won said 
david baker director of the ohio department of development and 
wed play the game again 
despite publicity heralding the 66 million display of 225 
artifacts spanning 26 centuries of chinese history sponsors in 
both cities who had predicted respectable profits reported stunning 
financial losses 
elling halvorson chairman of the seattlebased son of heaven 
inc said his organization lost 23 million leaving creditors 
and two charities that had pledged 1 million to the show with the 
debt 
in columbus the show lost nearly 17 million almost exactly 
the amount the state and city had pledged to guarantee creditors in 
case the exhibit lost money 
baker blamed the loss on the high cost of renovating a former 
high school to house the exhibit 
the loss prompted some ohio newspapers to delve into the 
financing of the exhibit it also focused more attention on plans 
for ameriflora 92 the citys multimilliondollar 1992 
commemoration of the 500th anniversary of christopher columbus 
arrival in the americas one local columnist already has dubbed the 
1992 event grandson of heaven 
it also surprised ohio legislators and controllers who said 
they never approved bakers promise that the state would guarantee 
1 million if the show lost money the state controlling board 
which approves many state contracts that are not competitively bid 
has delayed payment on the advice of ohio attorney general anthony 
j celebrezze jr he said such a deal was illegal 
the city has paid much of its 750000 guarantee 
baker contends that son of heaven paid off in other ways 
my departments calculations show that more taxes were paid to 
the community of columbus and the state of ohio as a result of son 
of heaven than all the public dollars going into it he said 
thats not the way we intended to pay for this but were net 
ahead on this were not behind 
but james kraft assistant director of the whitney museum of 
american art in new york said he would have been surprised had the 
shows made money 
you cant do something like this for the first time and expect 
it to be a success he said look at it as a business very 
few companies make money in the first two or three years of 
operation you have to do it once a year or once every two years to 
make it work 
david milenthal a spokesman for columbus together inc the 
organiztion that managed the exhibit in columbus said other cities 
looking to build tourism and economic development by subsidizing 
the arts should not be disuaded by the son of heaven losses 
if it hadnt been for the renovation of the high school at a 
cost 23 million for the exhibit this thing would have made 
money he said 
but other things we got from this cant be measured weve got 
a beautiful high school thats ready for the next show we had 
people come here from all 50 states and 50 countries people who 
wouldnt normally come here there were hundreds of articles 
written all over the world about the exhibit and columbus and ohio 
all of them positive you cant buy that kind of advertising 
nonetheless milenthal who is president of an advertising 
agency said that because of the controversy from the exhibit 
which was managed by his wife bonnie he will think twice the next 
time such an event is proposed 
i enjoyed every minute of the exhibit and working with it but 
when youve been slammed as badly as some of us involved have been 
slammed in the pasty few weeks i just dont know if id do it 
again he said 
</TEXT>
