<TEXT>
socialism has come full circle in 70 years a 
human life span so a personal memoir may be just the right medium 
for recounting its history 
heberto padilla cubas leading dissident intellectual has 
produced such a recollection in selfportrait of the other a 
book he calls a moral evaulation of myself it is also an 
evaluation of socialism 
in it padilla recalls his involvement with the cuban 
revolution how his enthusiasm soured and how the revolution 
punished him when he began to complain 
along the way he describes with a condensed and powerful style 
some memorable encounters with figures of the day jeanpaul 
sartre and albert camus che guevara and fidel castro and 
provides warm and respectful epitaphs for friends whom the 
revolution mistrusted among them the poet jose lezama lima and 
the playwright virgilio pineira 
padillas complaints led in 1971 to his imprisonment beatings 
and a public selfcriticism session the padilla case was a 
key juncture in the cuban revolution and an axiomatic event in the 
history of communism 
just as stalins show trials stripped many western intellectuals 
of their faith in soviet communism in the 1930s padillas 
treatment disabused liberal followers of castro of the notion that 
his tropical communism was blessed with a special saving grace 
a legion of prominent leftleaning writers among them sartre 
alberto moravia and susan sontag signed a protest letter to 
castro 
more importantly the episode drove a wedge into the virtually 
unanimous support that castro had enjoyed among latin 
intellectuals among the defectors was author mario vargas llosa 
who since has drifted steadily to the right today he is a 
conservative partys candidate for president of peru 
padillas generation was raised to view revolution as 
inevitable and to pursue it with ecclesiastic zeal as if leninism 
were the holy grail most of the influential hispanic writers 
described in selfportrait of the other had at least a brief 
courtship with a communist party 
now that a more pantheistic array of ideas has sprung from the 
shrouds of leninism the new generation of latin american poets 
are freer than we who believed that communism was the only hope 
for humanity padilla said in an interview from princeton nj 
where he has made his home since 1980 
we had all those old communist poets from the 1930s nicolas 
guillen the chilean pablo neruda spaniard rafael alberti 
riding on our backs but those people arent very influential 
anymore 
from the beginning padilla spurned the lush baroque imagery 
associated with neruda for a more lean poetics such as those of 
robert lowell and stjohn perse 
ideologically however he was keen on revolution after 
castros triumph he helped edit the literary supplement lunes de 
revolucion then went abroad working as a correspondent for the 
official cuban news agency and as a commercial diplomat 
a prolonged stay in moscow quashed his hopes for socialism and 
sharpened his sense of the pathetic both in himself and others 
in selfportrait he describes being ignored by castro 
during the latters visit to moscow we should have realized 
right then and there the kind of objects we were small animals of 
history which someone superior knew how to make use of and then 
discard 
yet he manages a kind of sympathy for anibal escalante a 
hardline communist who had lost out in a cuban power struggle and 
was consigned to a posting in the soviet union when snow covered 
moscow he seemed to cringe inside his black overcoat like a 
turtle in his shell fidel castro had decreed his extinction 
and he was never able to bring himself back to life 
padilla returned in the mid1960s to havana and his book of 
troubled verse out of the game won a national prize in 1968 
however the authorities found fault in padillas sarcasm and 
bitterness 
in the grim state security proceedings that followed his arrest 
in 1971 padillas aesthetic judgments were put on trial the cuban 
government was announcing that it no longer tolerated the personal 
criteria of its artists and wanted them to glorify the 
selfsacrifice required by the fatherland 
padilla never spells out whether he regrets having made the 
confession in which he also indicted more than 20 friends the 
reader is left to infer that he faced death or long imprisonment 
had he refused to do so 
under constant police surveillance padilla worked as a 
translator like the soviet writer boris pasternak in an earlier 
time until castro permitted him to emigrate in 1980 
padilla hopes some day to return home and with walls falling 
around the world he predicts that the one isolating cuba also will 
tumble 
it will be sudden like with ceausescu he said referring 
to romanias deposed leader i think it is inevitable 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

