hotels dealt with making their own beds and doing without prompt 
room service during the biggest hotel strike in hawaii history up 
to 7500 workers are on strike for better pay and benefits 
we have to make a living said caoili who makes about 850 
an hour if we dont do something there will be a time when 
these people cannot afford to live here 
nearby joe and jill cody of atlanta said that although they are 
enjoying their stay this has not been the hawaiian honeymoon they 
were expecting 
the biggest problem is having to make our own bed jill cody 
said they say theyre going to try to clean the rooms every 
other day 
not all was bad though the hotel gave them a 20 percent 
discount despite having to walk past lines of chanting strikers 
they said they are enjoying the palm trees and beaches that make 
hawaii a dream vacation destination for millions of tourists each 
year 
the walkout began saturday after negotiators for local 5 of the 
hotel and restaurant employees union rejected a management offer 
talks were to resume today at the behest of gov john waihee said 
federal mediator frank shoeppel 
the strike affects about onefourth of the 37000 hotel rooms in 
waikiki the states prime tourist destination and oneseventh of 
the 70000 hotel rooms in the state according to the hawaii 
visitors bureau 
the hotels were using nonunion staff and temporary hires to 
maintain limited operations 
jeanne park director of public relations for hilton hotels in 
hawaii said she has helped clear tables clean ashtrays and 
dispatch housekeeping services since the strike began 
nobody wins in this situation park said when i see my 
buddies out there on the picket lines i feel bad for them and i 
feel bad for us 
the union turned down a fouryear contract that includes what 
management calculates as a wageandbenefit package of 7 percent 
annually but which the union said is more like 4 percent a year 
hotel workers who do not receive tips average 922 an hour 
tipped workers earn an average of 487 an hour 
we cant afford to go on the way things are now said 
roberta bennett a restaurant hostess at the sheraton waikiki who 
makes 820 an hour 
bennett said she her husband and their baby live in a studio 
apartment for 600 a month with her hotel job a second job making 
tshirts and her husbands job with a tugboat company she said 
they barely meet expenses 
some tourists were unsympathetic to the strikers others tried 
to pay them no mind 
its almost contradictory theyre yelling scabs go home 
but its those scabs who are doing the jobs that bring the money 
here said bill carlile of alexandria va a guest at the ilikai 
hotel 
on a scale of 10 right now id give my vacation a seven 
said terry klein of victoria canada they really dont bug me 
and if theyve got a just cause go for it 
economists say the strike could badly damage hawaiis economy if 
it is long and if news reports give the impression the states 
tourist industry is paralyzed 
hotel officials stressed that all hotels are operating 
anyone planning a hawaii vacation can be assured of receiving 
the usual hawaiian hospitality said william crawford executive 
director of the council of hawaii hotels 
