<TEXT>
an environmental group is calling for an 
excise tax to pay for repainting up to 2 million homes and 
apartments and rid them of old leadbased paint that it says poses 
a health risk to millions of children 
in a report monday the environmental defense fund said more 
than 3 million preschool children suffer from lead poisoning from 
paint in their homes although such paint has not been sold for 
more than a dozen years 
the group said toxic levels of paint are found in many 
youngsters under age 6 because an estimated 2 million apartments 
and houses still have leadcontaining paint on the walls 
it has been estimated that the cost of ridding homes of lead 
paint could be 2000 to 10000 per house and the environmental 
group said congress should pass an excise tax on domestic and 
imported lead to help pay for the work 
we have built up an accumulation of lead from past uses that 
will not go away lead does not decay ellen silbergeld a 
senior toxicologist for the environmental group said at a news 
conference 
in an analysis based mainly on government statistics the 
organization said children in scores of cities have lead levels in 
their blood of more than 15 micrograms per deciliter of blood that 
is the level at which the environmental protection agency and other 
authorities believe childrn suffer some damage 
high levels of lead can cause serious brain damage but health 
experts say that even low levels of exposure can cause decreased 
intelligence shortterm memory loss and underachievement in school 
ms silbergeld said that while childrens exposure to lead from 
paint often was thought to come from eating paint chips it is 
widely believed now that paint dust normally released from paint 
as it ages poses the greatest threat to children 
the defense fund study said the greatest problem from lead paint 
is in older cities and is particularly acute among black children 
who often live in older housing in inner cities 
while nationally about 17 percent of preschool children are 
believed to have elevated lead levels in their blood almost 70 
percent of urban black children from poor families are estimated to 
exceed that level as are 35 percent of white children in similar 
circumstances the report said 
the group used national figures on exposure provided by the us 
public health service and separate statistics on the age of houses 
to produce an estimate as to what cities are likely to have the 
worst problem with children exposure to lead from paint 
this analysis showed 10 urban areas with roughly onefourth or 
more of the preschool children having elevated levels of lead that 
exceeded 15 micrograms per deciliter of blod 
the 10 areas and the percentage of children with those levels of 
lead were new york citynew jersey metropolitan area 338 
percent newark nj 30 percent jersey city nj 293 percent 
cleveland 274 percent new orleans 266 percent philadelphia 
264 percent chicago 255 percent baltimore 249 percent 
pattersoncliftonpassaic nj 25 percent and trenton nj 
245 percent 
