rapid growth in electricity demand the virginia power co has 
received federal permission to buy electric power from a 400 
million plant that a subsidiary of japans mitsubishi corp plans 
to build in central virginia 
the deal was approved last week by the federal energy regulatory 
commission according to todays editions of the washington post 
several industry experts call the deal the first of its kind in 
this country a fullsize conventional power plant built and 
operated by an independent company that is in the business of 
manufacturing electricity for the wholesale market 
the plant will burn natural gas supplied by a new 120mile 65 
million pipeline that will link gas lines in loudoun county and the 
tidewater virginia area 
traditionally utility companies have built their own plants in 
addition for the past decade federal law has required power 
companies to purchase power generated by small independent 
producers burning renewable fuels but the mitsubishi project was 
negotiated outside the scope of that law the newspaper reported 
while the mitsubishi plant falls outside the normal channels of 
stateregulated utilities the rate it proposes charging for the 
power does not virginia power and mitsubishi have agreed on a rate 
equivalent to what it would cost virginia power to produce the 
electricity in a plant it had built 
officials said the deal should not effect the bills of virginia 
power retail customers 
mitsubishi has agreed to bear the cost if it is forced to pay 
more to produce the power than its sales contract allows it to 
recapture from virginia power the company is willing to take the 
risk because it gains entry to a new area of business 
