<TEXT>
raising the cost of postage isnt like 
stamping a new price on cereal or changing the sticker on a car 
congress which once had final say on stamp prices surrendered 
that authority in 1971 when it established the quasiindependent 
us postal service 
but it set up a lengthy and complex system for rate changes when 
they do occur 
as in any business postal managers keep track of their costs 
and income and decide when they are losing money and a rate 
increase is needed theres no longer a taxpayer subsidy to pay the 
difference 
the first step is to go to the board of governors a 
presidentially appointed panel that supervises the post office 
operation 
if the board agrees with the managers it votes to request a 
rate increase and sends that plan along with a detailed 
justification to the independent postal rate commission 
the commission a separate presidentially appointed board has 
10 months to consider the request it solicits comments from 
individuals and businesses holds hearings and conducts studies 
before sending a series of recommendations back to the board of 
governors 
if those recommendations are the same as the original proposal 
or close enough that the board finds them acceptable the governors 
can set a date for the new rates to take effect 
if the governors disagree they can ask the commission to 
reconsider come up with a new set of proposals themselves or if 
they vote unanimously can overrule the commission and put the 
original proposed rate into effect 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

