<TEXT>
regulating a securities firm like drexel 
burnham lambert inc without financial data on its parent company 
is like being a doctor who can only examine part of the body the 
head of the securities and exchange commission told a senate panel 
on tuesday 
sec chairman richard c breeden used a budget hearing before the 
commerce subcommittee of the senate appropriations committee as an 
opportunity to lobby for additional authority 
questioned about the recent collapse of drexel breeden said one 
difficulty for the sec was lack of data about the parent holding 
company which filed for bankruptcy code protection last month 
the sec regulates brokerdealers but not their parent companies 
which dont have to disclose their financial status 
legislation pending in both the house and senate would give the 
sec access to such financial data 
breeden likened the limitations on such information to being a 
physician who can only look at the right arm from the elbow to 
the wrist its very unrealistic 
the bush administration is seeking 1924 million for the sec in 
1991 a 14 percent increase over the 1990 appropriation of 1687 
million 
breeden noted that congress should be mindful that sec revenue 
production through filing fees have significantly exceeded its 
appropriations 
he pointed out that in 1989 while receiving only 1426 million 
in appropriations the sec generated 2138 million in fees 
but sen ernest f hollings dsc chairman of the 
subcommittee asked why the administration was seeking to increase 
sec fees an estimated 80 million in 1991 
why are you increasing the fees when you got more than enough 
to run the business did you recommend any increases he asked 
this proposal is not a commission proposal said breeden 
ahh there we go said hollings prompting laughter in the 
cramped hearing room in the capitol building 
