<TEXT>
a federal judge on tuesday refused to bar a 
former philips industries executive accused of insider trading from 
selling more stock in the company but froze about 1 million of 
his assets 
us district court judge walter rice approved a request by the 
securities and exchange commission for the temporary freeze on 
robert h brethens assets being held in an escrow account the sec 
sought the freeze to assure payment of any future damages 
the sec has asked the judge for a preliminary injunction to keep 
brethen a former philips vice chairman from trading his philips 
stock rice refused to grant a temporary restraining order pending 
a hearing 
an sec civil lawsuit against brethen last week alleged he used 
nonpublic information about unfavorable company news to avoid 
570000 in losses in the stock market in january when he sold 
109733 shares for more than 2 million on the new york stock 
exchange 
the sec claimed brethen would continue to violate securities 
laws unless he is restrained from further securities trading 
the judge had postponed a ruling on the temporary restraining 
order from last week after the sec alleged brethen lied to the 
commission and tried to cover up his access to inside information 
the case is considered unusual because the government said three 
attorneys and a stockbroker for brethen have testified that they 
advised him not to sell the stock because it may violate securities 
laws 
brethens violations are continuing jeffrey zuckerman 
assistant regional administrator for the sec said in a letter to 
the judge brethen was engaging in an ongoing violation in 
january when he was caught in the breach by the commission 
rather than cooperate with the commission however brethen 
compounded his violations by engaging in an attempt to cover up 
the letter said 
sec attorney james tyne said in court last week that brethen may 
be financially strapped because of a new business venture celstar 
group inc and might lose the 1 million he had earlier agreed to 
place in escrow after the sec launched an investigation 
david cupps brethens attorney said his client has cooperated 
fully with the sec including giving voluntary testimony and 
should have his money returned to conduct his business 
brethen 63 retired at the end of last year from philips a 
manufacturer or components for construction and recreational 
vehicles previously he had been president and chief executive of 
the compny 
cupps said brethen no longer has access to inside information 
and sold some of the stock only after an attorney assured him doing 
so would be proper 
but tyne said there was a very strong likelihood of repeated 
violations because brethen still owns 100000 shares of philis 
stock misled the sec and ignored the advice of at least three 
lawyers not to sell the shares 
the sec alleged brethen sold the stock while possessing 
nonpublic information that philips earnings would be dramatically 
lower than expected for the final quarter of 1989 which would have 
an adverse impact on a proposed buyout of philips 
